\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

 an odd integer, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 a non-negative integer.
 This is very simply the tree with rows
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray*}
\frac{0}{1}\quad &  & \quad\frac{1}{1}\\
 & \frac{1}{2}\\
\frac{1}{4}\qquad &  & \qquad\frac{3}{4}\\
\frac{1}{8}\qquad\frac{3}{8}\quad &  & \quad\frac{5}{8}\qquad\frac{7}{8}\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

 This tree, the dyadic rational tree, also has a matrix representation for
 converting a sequence of left-right moves to the value of the dyadic fraction
 located at the resulting node.
 The left and right dyadic matrices are 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
L_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}\end{array}\right)\;\;\textrm{ and }\;\; R_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
\frac{1}{2} & \frac{1}{2}\end{array}\right)\label{eq:dyadic L and R}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 and these generate what will be called the two-dimensional 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

dyadic representation
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of moves on the binary tree.
