\begin_layout Standard
The dyadic matrix that results from a sequence of left and right moves is
 clearly not unimodular.
 However, insofar as it labels a set of moves on the binary tree, it is
 isomorphic to the matrices arising in the Farey representation.
 There is a (unique) matrix corresponding to each node in the tree, and
 these can be trivially identified with one another.
 The representations are not, however 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

equivalent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

: there does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 exist a similarity matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 that caries the one to the other.
 That is, the equations
\begin_inset Formula \[
SL_{D}=L_{C}S\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
SR_{D}=R_{C}S\]

\end_inset

 are satisfied only by 
\begin_inset Formula $S=0$
\end_inset

.
 Here, we wrote 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{C}$
\end_inset

 for the 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:L and R"

\end_inset

, in order to distinguish them from the dyadic 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These two representations are developed and examined in greater detail in
 another paper (ref my paper on Minkowski question mark), and the details
 will not be reproduced here; the focus of this paper are the three-dimensional
 and the higher-dimensional representations.
 However, there are several important points that must be noted, in order
 to avoid confusion.
 Most important is to understand that the moves on the binary tree are 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 isomorphic to the modular group.
 Although it can be shown that 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{C}$
\end_inset

 generate all of 
\begin_inset Formula $PSL(2,\mathbb{Z})$
\end_inset

, the 
\emph on
non-negative
\emph default
 powers do not.
 The non-negative powers generate only what is called a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

monoid
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 or a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

semigroup
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

, and not a full group, because the inverse elements are missing.
 The monoid does not contain the elements 
\begin_inset Formula $L^{-1}$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{-1}$
\end_inset

 or any strings containing these elements.
 Although it may at first seem seem that the negative powers correspond
 to upward walks on the binary tree, this is not so.
 The meaning of the negative powers in terms of their action on the tree
 cannot be made consistent or even complete.
 Thus, while the monoid can be formally extended to a full group by adjoining
 the formal inverses, the resulting group no longer describes motion on
 a binary tree.
 That is, the monoid acts on the binary tree; but it is impossible to extend
 this action to an action of the full group.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Another critical aspect make note of is that the action of the monoid is
 an action on a certain set of intervals of the real number line.
 When the infinite binary tree is labelled either with the dyadic fractions
 or with the Farey fractions, it may be shown that any fraction occurring
 on the left is always strictly less then another fraction on the right.
 Thus, the binary tree extending under any given node has distinct and unique
 (Cauchy) limits to the left and to the right, thus defining an interval
 of the real number line.
 The subtree under any given node is clearly isomorphic to the tree as a
 whole.
 Finally, one may note that the dyadic rationals are dense in the reals,
 as are the Farey fractions.
 In fact, every rational shows up somewhere on the Farey tree.
 These properties make it clear that the act of navigating to any particular
 sub-node of the binary tree is the same as a map from one interval (say
 the unit interval) to a certain specific subinterval.
 It is not possible to navigate to just any interval whatsoever; these are
 constrained.
 A detailed discussion of which subintervals are allowed, and how to enumerate
 them, is given elsewhere (cf.
 my Minkowski question mark paper).
 Roughly, though, it may be said that the allowed intervals may be enumerated
 as 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathbb{Q\times\mathbb{N}}$
\end_inset

.
 It will become apparent, in the text of this paper, that the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

allowed
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 intervals are precisely those for which a period-doubling fractal is self-simil
ar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Numerical representations 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The set of strings in two letters is clearly isomorphic to the binary numbers,
 in that any given string in 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 can be converted to a string on 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, which may then be taken to be a binary number.
 Fractions such as 1/3, as well as irrational numbers correspond to strings
 of infinite length.
 A convenient alternate notation is in terms of continued fractions.
 One searches for a matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 with the properties 
\begin_inset Formula $r^{2}=1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R=rLr$
\end_inset

.
 The first property suggests that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a 'reflection'.
 It follows from these properties that 
\begin_inset Formula $R^{n}=rL^{n}r$
\end_inset

 and so any string in 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

 can be written as a string in 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

.
 In what follows, the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 is used for 
\begin_inset Formula $L$
\end_inset

, so that the strings are in 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 A general string of the form 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma=L^{a_{1}}R^{a_{2}}L^{a_{3}}\ldots\]

\end_inset

 may therefore also be written as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...\]

\end_inset

While the first form has a natural representation in terms of a binary number,
 the second has a natural representation in terms of the continued fraction
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
[0;a_{1},a_{2},a_{3},\ldots]=\frac{1}{a_{1}+\frac{1}{a_{2}+\frac{1}{a_{3}+\ldots}}}\]

\end_inset

 The numerical value of these two forms are not the same; the explicit map
 between these two numerical representations is given by the Minkowski question
 mark function.
 For the dyadic representation 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{D}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{D}$
\end_inset

 of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:dyadic L and R"

\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
0 & \frac{1}{2}\end{array}\right)\;\;\textrm{ and }\;\; r_{D}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
1 & -1\end{array}\right)\label{eq:dyadic g and d}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 while those corresponding to the Farey 
\begin_inset Formula $L_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{C}$
\end_inset

are
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
g_{C}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
1 & 0\\
1 & 1\end{array}\right)\;\;\textrm{ and }\;\; r_{C}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
0 & 1\\
1 & 0\end{array}\right)\label{eq:farey g and d}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Interpreted as operators on the binary tree, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 corresponds to taking the left branch, while 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a mirror-reflection of the tree.
 Expressed in terms of intervals, 
\begin_inset Formula $g$
\end_inset

 maps an interval to the left-half of the interval, while 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 is a reflection of the interval about its center point.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is the label on a node of the dyadic tree (that is, if 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 is a real number), then one has the explicit representation 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{D}(x)=\frac{x}{2}\quad\mbox{ and }\quad r_{D}(x)=1-x\]

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $x\in[0,1]$
\end_inset

.
 The above holds because the distribution of the dyadics is uniform with
 regards to the canonical topological measure on the real number line, and
 thus, any subtree will map back to the whole tree linearly.
