\begin_layout Subsection
Multi-fractals
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The uniqueness of the Takagi curve for each distinct value of 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 implies that we can use it to define an (incomplete) set of basis vectors
 for functions on the unit interval.
 That is, there is a large class of functions on the unit interval 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 that can be expressed as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
f(x)=\int_{0}^{\infty}c(w)\, t_{w}(x)\; dw\]

\end_inset

 for some function 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\mathbb{R}^{+}\rightarrow\mathbb{R}$
\end_inset

 or more generally 
\begin_inset Formula $c:\mathbb{R}^{+}\rightarrow\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, for example, the function of equation 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:strange-expo"

\end_inset

 be expressed in this form.
 The resulting function 
\begin_inset Formula $f(x)$
\end_inset

 does not have any particular self-similarity properties, but its decomposition
 does.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
The Cantor Polynomials 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The action of a group element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 on the Takagi curve can be written as 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}(\gamma_{D}(x))=p_{\gamma}(w)+x\, q_{\gamma}(w)+w^{M_{\gamma}}t_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset

 for some polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 and positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 where we use the subscript 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 to denote that they depend on the particular 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma$
\end_inset

 chosen.
 A brief bit of scratching shows what the 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 polynomial is; but 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is harder.
 For 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}$
\end_inset

 as before, one has 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{\gamma}=a_{1}+...+a_{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Writing out the binary expansion for 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{D}(1)$
\end_inset

 in terms of binary digits 
\begin_inset Formula $b_{k}\in\left\{ 0,1\right\} $
\end_inset

, one has 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\gamma_{D}(1) & = & \sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\nonumber \\
\, & = & \begin{array}{ccccc}
0. & \underbrace{000...000} & \underbrace{111...111} & \underbrace{000...000} & ...\\
\, & a_{1} & a_{2} & a_{3} & \,\end{array}\label{eq:}\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where, as usual, one takes the expansion such that the final binary digits
 repeat forever, without upsetting the count 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{N}$
\end_inset

 of the previous digits; that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
b_{k}=\left\{ \begin{array}{ccc}
1 & \;\textrm{ for N odd, }\; & \forall k>M\\
0 & \;\textrm{ for N even, }\; & \forall k>M\end{array}\right.\label{eq:}\end{equation}

\end_inset

