\begin_layout Standard
It can be readily worked out that the factor of 
\begin_inset Formula $2l+1$
\end_inset

, which is needed to enumerate the eigenfunctions, does not add any new
 or interesting complications to the overall symmetry.
 With a minimum of effort, one can quickly see that these curves transform
 in a fashion similar to the Takagi Curve.
 Starting with 
\begin_inset Formula $g,$
\end_inset

 we have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[g\psi_{z,l}\right](x)=\left[\psi_{z,l}g\right](x)=\psi_{z,l}(\frac{x}{2})=\exp\left((2l+1)\pi ix\right)+z\psi_{z,l}(x)\]

\end_inset

 and for reflection,
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[r\psi_{z,l}\right](x)=\left[\psi_{z,l}r\right](x)=\psi_{z,l}(1-x)=\psi_{z,l}(-x)\]

\end_inset

 Concatenating group elements proceeds in a fashion similar to before.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{D}^{3}r_{D}g_{D}^{2}(x)=\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\]

\end_inset

 and so 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[g^{3}rg^{2}\psi_{z}\right](x)=\psi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\right)=\exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\right)+z\psi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\]

\end_inset

 where we've taken, for convenience, 
\begin_inset Formula $l=0$
\end_inset

.
 Peeling off one group element at a time, we finally get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
\psi_{z}\left(\frac{1}{8}-\frac{x}{32}\right) & = & \exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{4}-\frac{x}{16}\right)\right)+z\,\exp\left(i\pi\left(\frac{1}{2}-\frac{x}{8}\right)\right)+\nonumber \\
 & + & z^{2}\exp\left(i\pi\left(1-\frac{x}{4}\right)\right)+z^{3}\exp\left(-i\pi\frac{x}{2}\right)+\nonumber \\
 & + & z^{4}\exp\left(-i\pi x\right)+z^{5}\psi_{z}\left(-x\right)\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 However, this obscures the true form of the transformation, which is exhibited
 more clearly if we write the above as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{eqnarray}
g^{3}rg^{2}\psi_{z} & = & \psi_{z}g^{3}rg^{2}\nonumber \\
 & = & Eg^{3}rg^{2}+z\, Eg^{2}rg^{2}+z^{2}Egrg^{2}+z^{3}Erg^{2}+z^{4}Erg+z^{5}\psi_{z}r\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

 where we defined 
\begin_inset Formula $E(x)\equiv\exp(2\pi ix)=\psi_{z=0}(x)$
\end_inset

.
 Just to be perfectly clear, in the above expression, we mean functional
 composition whenever two elements are next to each other, with the exception
 of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

, which is just plain multiplication.
 The operator 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 has the effect of peeling off one group element at a time, and converting
 it to a 
\begin_inset Formula $z.$
\end_inset

 The result is a funny polynomial which captures the action of the group
 element.
 The funny polynomial is the orbit of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{z}$
\end_inset

