 We abstain from trying to write the corresponding polynomial for the general
 element 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=g^{a_{1}}rg^{a_{2}}rg^{a_{3}}r...rg^{a_{N}}$
\end_inset

 mostly because it would be quite ungainly.
 We note only that the highest power of 
\begin_inset Formula $z$
\end_inset

 will be 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1}+a_{2}+...+a_{N}$
\end_inset

 and also that 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 can take the place of a minus sign, in that 
\begin_inset Formula $(Er)(x)=E(r(x))=E(1-x)=E(-x)$
\end_inset

, which remains in place, until the next 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

 cancels it out.
 None-the-less, this polynomial is curious, and calls for further development.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Topologically Conjugate Maps
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The Modular Group Symmetry describes not just this peculiar handful of curves,
 but in fact a large class of curves.
 Any monotonically increasing function 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(x)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi(1)=1$
\end_inset

 can be used to build topologically conjugate maps.
 For the tent map, we write 
\begin_inset Formula $\sigma(x)=(\phi\circ\tau\circ\phi^{-1})(x)$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula \[
s_{w}(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}w^{k}(\phi\circ\tau^{k+1}\circ\phi^{-1})(x)\]

\end_inset

 which transforms under the action of 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\phi}(x)=(\phi\circ g_{D}\circ\phi^{-1})(x)\]

\end_inset

 as 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\left[gs_{w}\right](x)\equiv s_{w}(g_{\phi}(x))=x+ws_{w}(x)\]

\end_inset

 This transformation law follows rather trivially, because we had 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{n+1}g_{D}=\tau^{n}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $n>0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $(\tau g_{D})(x)=(1)(x)=x$
\end_inset

.
 In the same vein, we define 
\begin_inset Formula \[
r_{\phi}(x)=(\phi\circ r_{D}\circ\phi^{-1})(x)\]

\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{D}(x)=1-x$
\end_inset

.
 Working with these two generators, we can construct the generic element
 very easily, as 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma_{\phi}=\phi\circ\gamma_{D}\circ\phi^{-1}$
\end_inset

, and discover, of course, that 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{w}$
\end_inset

 transforms under exactly the same three-dimensional representation that
 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}$
\end_inset

 does.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Lets quickly examine a specific example, the Logistic map of unit height.
 This map is conjugate to the tent map, and the conjugating functions are
 given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi(x)=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\cos\left(\pi x\right)\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\phi^{-1}(x)=\frac{1}{\pi}\arccos\left(1-2x\right)\]

\end_inset

 so that we get 
\begin_inset Formula \[
\lambda(x)\equiv(\phi\circ\tau\circ\phi^{-1})(x)=4x(x-1)\]

\end_inset

 Then, iterating on this map, we get 
\begin_inset Formula \[
L_{w}(x)=\sum_{k=0}^{\infty}w^{k}\lambda^{k+1}(x)\]

\end_inset

 The generators of the symmetry group for this conjugating function are
 
\begin_inset Formula \[
g_{\phi}(x)=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}\sqrt{1-x}\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $r_{\phi}(x)=r_{D}(x)=1-x$
\end_inset

.
 The graph of this curve is not that interesting and generally resembles
 that of the Takagi Curve shown in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:The-Takagi-Landsberg-Curve"

\end_inset

, and thus we do not graph it here.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although constructed from a parabola, do not confuse this curve with the
 curve that transforms under the 4D rep: this is because 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda^{k+1}(x)\neq\lambda(2^{k}x)$
\end_inset

: in one case, we are iterating, in the other, we are making copies.
 In the above discussion, we've conflated two different concepts: the act
 of iteration, and the construction of the Takagi curve.
 We can do this because iterating the tent map just makes copies of the
 map: 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau^{k+1}(x)=\tau(2^{k}x)$
\end_inset

.
 This is generally not the case for other maps, and the tent map is unique
 in this way (XXX??? right? or is there some other bizarre map that behaves
 like this?) Thus, we have an important corollary here: 
\series bold
curves generated by iterated maps always transform under the three-dimensional
 representation, and not the higher-dimensional representations
\series default
.
 The higher-dimensional representations cannot be made conjugate to iterated
 maps, because if they could be, they'd transform under the three-dimensional
 rep, a contradiction.
 We've subtly failed to mention one limitation: not all iterated maps can
 be made conjugate to the tent map.
 It is not clear to this author, at this time, which maps can and cannot
 be made conjugate to the tent map, and answering this question should provide
 insight into the nature of iteration.
 
\end_layout

