\begin_layout Section
The de Rham Construction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In a classic 1957 paper
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "DeR57"

\end_inset

, Georges de Rham constructs a class of curves, and proves that these curves
 are everywhere continuous but are nowhere differentiable (more precisely,
 are not differentiable at the rationals).
 In addition, he shows how the curves may be parameterized by a real number
 in the unit interval.
 The construction is simple.
 This section illustrates some of these curves.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider a pair of contracting maps of the plane 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{0}:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{1}:\mathbb{R}^{2}\to\mathbb{R}^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 By the Banach fixed point theorem, such contracting maps should have fixed
 points 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Assume that each fixed point lies in the basin of attraction of the other
 map, and furthermore, that the one applied to the fixed point of the other
 yields the same point, that is, 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{1}(p_{0})=d_{0}(p_{1})\label{eq:continuity condition}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 Then these maps can be used to construct a certain continuous curve between
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider next the expansion in binary digits of a real number 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, as given previously in eqn.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq: binary expansion"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula \[
x=\sum_{k=1}^{\infty}\frac{b_{k}}{2^{k}}\]

\end_inset

 The de Rham curve is then a map characterized by the continuous parameter
 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{x}=d_{b_{1}}\circ\; d_{b_{2}}\circ\,\ldots\:\circ\, d_{b_{k}}\circ\,\ldots\label{eq:de-Rham curve}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The above map will map points in the common basin of attraction of the
 two maps to a single point.
 De Rham provides a simple proof that the resulting set of points form a
 continuous curve as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, and that furthermore, this function is not differentiable in any conventional
 sense.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
De Rham provides several examples.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $z=u+iv$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $a\in\mathbb{C}$
\end_inset

 be a constant such that 
\begin_inset Formula $|a|<1$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $|a-1|<1$
\end_inset

.
 Then consider the maps 
\begin_inset Formula \[
d_{0}(z)=az\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
d_{1}(z)=a+(1-a)z\]

\end_inset

 These two maps clearly have fixed points at 
\begin_inset Formula $z=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $z=1$
\end_inset

, respectively.
 The generated curve is is the non-differentiable curve of 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Ces
\backslash
`{a}ro
\end_layout

\end_inset

 and Faber, now known more generally as the 
\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

L
\backslash
'{e}vy
\end_layout

\end_inset

