\begin_layout Section
Markov chains 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Markov chains are commonly studied in the theory of probability.
 Of all possible Markov chains, the chains for a stationary process are
 most frequently discussed, because they have a simple, tractable theory.
 In this section, we note that the de Rham construction can be used to create
 a set of non-stationary Markov chains that are none-the-less tractable.
 These are essentially a minor variant on the above construction, but are
 noted because of the importance of Markov chains in general.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A Markov chain may be defined in several ways.
 For the purposes here, a Markov chain may be defined as a sequence of 
\begin_inset Formula $n\times n$
\end_inset

 matrices, the probability transition matrices, having the property that
 they preserve the norm of probability vectors.
 A probability vector is very simply a vector 
\begin_inset Formula $(p_{1},p_{2},\ldots,p_{n})$
\end_inset

 where all of the entries are real and positive, and sum to one.
 One may then deduce that the transition matrix must have entries that are
 real, and lie between zero and one, with the entries in each column summing
 to one as well.
 The sequence of matrices are multiplied together to form the chain.
 Properties of the chain that may be studied are expected value of the probabili
ty vector (the fixed point), the means-square variance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is readily seen that the general form of a two-dimensional dyadic chain
 will be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
d_{0}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
a & b\\
1-a & 1-b\end{array}\right)\;\textrm{ and }\; d_{1}=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
c & d\\
1-c & 1-d\end{array}\right)\label{eq:Markov matrices}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 The fixed point 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}$
\end_inset

is given by 
\begin_inset Formula \[
p_{0}=\left(\begin{array}{c}
\frac{b}{1-a+b}\\
\frac{1-a}{1-a+b}\end{array}\right)\]

\end_inset

 and likewise for 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{1}$
\end_inset

.
 Although there is not overt requirement for the resulting de Rham curve
 to be continuous, one might ask what constraints continuity imposes.
 The answer is that one must have 
\begin_inset Formula \[
d=c-(1-a+b)\]

\end_inset

 The requirement that 
\begin_inset Formula $0\le d\le1$
\end_inset

 translates into the condition 
\begin_inset Formula \[
c+a\le1+b\]

\end_inset

 A pair of typical figures are shown in figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "cap:Markov-chain-curves"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

