\begin_layout Section
Symbolic dynamics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The construction and symmetry properties are not limited to continuous curves.
 Any system with a symbolic dynamics in two symbols is naturally parameterized
 through real numbers.
 Consider, for example, the symbolic dynamics of the tent map of unit height.
 By picking an initial value, and then iterating on the tent map, one will
 get a sequence of values.
 For each iteration, write down the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 if the value is less than 1/2, and write the letter 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 if the value is more than 1/2.
 The result of the iteration will be an infinitely long string composed
 of the letters 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

, sometimes called the 
\emph on
orbit
\emph default
 of the initial value.
 This string is the so-called symbolic dynamics of the iterated unit-height
 tent map.
 It can be shown that the symbolic dynamics of the iteration precisely and
 completely defines the iteration.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
What is notable here is that any string in two letters can be exactly mapped
 to a real number, by interpreting it as the dyadic expansion of that number.
 In this case, let 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{k}$
\end_inset

 be zero if the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th letter is 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and let it be one if the 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

'th letter is 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

.
 We then define the value of a symbolic string to be 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
s(x)=\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}c_{k}2^{-k}\label{eq:orbit value}\end{equation}

\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 was the initial value that was iterated.
 The figure 
