\begin_layout Section
Analytic Continuation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
So far, we have been looking at the Takagi curve as a function of 
\begin_inset Formula $x,$
\end_inset

 holding 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 fixed.
 One may also explore the dependency on 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 for fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

.
 For any fixed 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

, the Takagi curve is analytic in 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

, by construction, with radius of convergence of 1.
 One task is to describe the the set of 
\begin_inset Formula $x$
\end_inset

 for which the function may be analytically continued to values of 
\begin_inset Formula $\left|w\right|>1$
\end_inset

.
 There are many easy cases.
 For example, 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(0)=0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(1/2)=1$
\end_inset

 are trivial, and 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(1/4)=w+1/2$
\end_inset

 is clearly entire.
 Continuing, we have
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{2^{n}}\right)=\frac{1}{2^{n-1}}\;\frac{1-2^{n}w^{n}}{1-2w}\]

\end_inset

 which is a polynomial of finite degree, without any poles (there is no
 pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1/2$
\end_inset

), and thus entire.
 Its not hard to see, for any integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

, that 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{w}(p/2^{n})$
\end_inset

 will be a finite polynomial in 
\begin_inset Formula $w.$
\end_inset

 By contrast, 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{3}\right)=\frac{2}{3(1-w)}\]

\end_inset

 has a simple pole at 
\begin_inset Formula $w=1$
\end_inset

.
 Other values include 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{5}\right)=\frac{2}{5}\cdot\frac{1+2w}{1-w^{2}}\]

\end_inset

and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{7}\right)=\frac{2}{7}\cdot\frac{1+2w+3w^{2}}{1-w^{3}}\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{9}\right)=\frac{2}{9}\cdot\frac{1+2w+4w^{2}}{1-w^{3}}\]

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula \[
t_{w}\left(\frac{1}{11}\right)=\frac{2}{11}\cdot\frac{1+2w+4w^{2}+6w^{3}+5w^{4}}{1-w^{5}}\]

\end_inset

 all of which appear to have simple poles at various roots of unity.
 Note that for all of these cases, the limiting asymptotic behavior for
 large 
\begin_inset Formula $w$
\end_inset

 is finite.
 
\end_layout

